data.content:
This code **doesn't actually call `Thread.Abort`**, so it won't throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8. However, the `Thread`-per-item pattern is outdated and lacks cancellation support — exactly the gap `Thread.Abort` was typically used to fill.

Here's the modern .NET 8 approach using **`Task` + `CancellationToken`** (cooperative cancellation):

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items,
        CancellationToken ct = default)
    {
        var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(
            () => Process(item, ct), ct));

        await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        // simulate work
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

**Key migration points:**

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `ThreadAbortException` | `OperationCanceledException` |
| `new Thread().Start()` | `Task.Run()` |
| `Thread.Join()` | `await Task.WhenAll()` |

**Why `Thread.Abort` was removed:** It could corrupt process state by interrupting code at arbitrary points (e.g., mid-`finally` block). Cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken` is safe because the work checks for cancellation at well-defined points.

If you have actual `Thread.Abort` call sites elsewhere in your codebase, the fix is always the same: pass a `CancellationToken` and replace `Abort()` with `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`.
